A comprehensive DNA barcode database for Central European beetles with a focus on Germany: adding more than 3500 identified species to BOLD

Lars Hendrich, 
Joint first authors.

Frank Köhler,

First published: 03 December 2014
https://doi.org/10.1111/1755-0998.12354
Citations: 146

Abstract

Beetles are the most diverse group of animals and are crucial for ecosystem functioning. In many countries, they are well established for environmental impact assessment, but even in the well-studied Central European fauna, species identification can be very difficult. A comprehensive and taxonomically well-curated DNA barcode library could remedy this deficit and could also link hundreds of years of traditional knowledge with next generation sequencing technology. However, such a beetle library is missing to date. This study provides the globally largest DNA barcode reference library for Coleoptera for 15 948 individuals belonging to 3514 well-identified species (53% of the German fauna) with representatives from 97 of 103 families (94%). This study is the first comprehensive regional test of the efficiency of DNA barcoding for beetles with a focus on Germany. Sequences ≥500 bp were recovered from 63% of the specimens analysed (15 948 of 25 294) with short sequences from another 997 specimens. Whereas most specimens (92.2%) could be unambiguously assigned to a single known species by sequence diversity at CO1, 1089 specimens (6.8%) were assigned to more than one Barcode Index Number (BIN), creating 395 BINs which need further study to ascertain if they represent cryptic species, mitochondrial introgression, or simply regional variation in widespread species. We found 409 specimens (2.6%) that shared a BIN assignment with another species, most involving a pair of closely allied species as 43 BINs were involved. Most of these taxa were separated by barcodes although sequence divergences were low. Only 155 specimens (0.97%) show identical or overlapping clusters.

Introduction

Beetles are the most diverse order of insects with nearly 400 000 described species (Zhang 2011). The fauna of Germany includes 6631 species in 103 families while 8985 species occur in Central Europe (Köhler & Klausnitzer 1998). These species possess enormous morphological and ecological diversity and provide numerous ecosystem services – with many species wood boring, herbivorous or carnivorous and adapted to both terrestrial and aquatic habitats (Köhler & Klausnitzer 1998), whereas many larvae are inhabitants of subterranean habitats. The beetle fauna of Europe is well known as there is a very active community of professional and amateur entomologists studying their taxonomy and ecology. This is especially true for the Central European fauna which has a taxonomic history that predates Linnaeus. Because their extreme species richness is coupled with morphological, ecological and behavioural diversity, beetles are widely used for environmental impact assessments (EIAs), ecological studies and monitoring activities (Foster et al. 1989; Lindhe et al. 2005; Jurc 2012; Bicknell et al. 2014). While their value for EIAs is undisputed, there remains a need to better understand habitat requirements, especially of their larvae, as well as interactions between species (Rainio & Niemelä 2003). This often requires improved taxonomic tools.

Certain beetle species are serious pests in agriculture and forestry, with some causing economic losses of billions of euros (Germain et al. 2013; Jordal & Kambestad 2014). Invasive species, such as the Asian ladybird, Harmonia axyridis Pallas, 1773, are now a threat to the native European Coccinellidae fauna (Fischer 2013; Lombaert et al. 2014). On the other hand, the ladybird Coccinella septempunctata Linnaeus, 1758 is useful for pest control (Bianchi et al. 2013) and the defence secretions of Harmonia axyridis have medical applications (Röhrich et al. 2012).

DNA barcoding provides an efficient method for biodiversity assessment as it meets the need for fast, efficient and reliable species identification at this time of climate change and massive habitat destruction (Hebert & Gregory 2005; Valentini et al. 2009). This approach is arguably the best way to handle the vast diversity of invertebrates which are crucial for ecosystem functioning but often poorly known taxonomically. DNA barcoding also has the power to connect different life stages such as eggs, larvae and adults. As such, it can link hundreds of years of taxonomic, ecological, faunistic and ethological studies with ultra-high-throughput sequencing the genomic era. The latter approach will have great benefits for many application-oriented fields, especially in agriculture and forestry where the rapid and reliable identification of bulk samples is critical.

Strongly validated, reliable species libraries are of importance as climatic change and global distribution of goods facilitate the movement of invasive species, which, after being introduced, might exhibit greater ecological damage outside their native habitat. However, identification success is only as good as the underlying database (Kvist 2013). To date, most published DNA barcoding studies dealing with insects have focused on Hymenoptera and Lepidoptera, while few recent studies have examined the hyperdiverse Coleoptera (Woodcock et al. 2013; Pentinsaari et al. 2014). Bergsten et al. found that a minimum of 70 specimens needed to be analysed to sample 95% of its intraspecific variation in the species they examined (Bergsten et al. 2012a). However, the local DNA barcode library developed in this study provides an important foundation for future efforts to better assess intraspecific variation projects. This publication begins to address this deficit by releasing the largest Coleoptera barcode reference library to date, focused on the heart of Europe. The records provide coverage for 15 948 beetle specimens (3514 species), 53% of the German and 39% of the Central European fauna (Köhler & Klausnitzer 1998). This release is a direct result of the Barcoding Fauna Bavarica project (http://www.faunabavarica.de) led by the Bavarian State Collection of Zoology (SNSB-ZSM) with support from the Bavarian State Government (Haszprunar 2009). With an area of 70 000 km2, Bavaria is the largest German state and possesses all major habitat types in Germany (except coastal regions) and harbours 90% of the terrestrial and freshwater species known from Germany. Due to its diverse habitats, Bavaria also hosts approximately 70% of the Central European fauna. In 2012, DNA barcoding was elevated to a national mission through the establishment of the ‘German Barcode of Life (GBOL)’ project (http://www.bolgermany.de), led by the Zoologisches Forschungsmuseum Alexander Koenig in Bonn (ZFMK), but involving strong participation by other German institutions including the SNSB-ZSM. In close cooperation with the Biodiversity Institute of Ontario (BIO, Guelph, Canada), the German barcoding projects aim to assemble a DNA barcode library for all animal species present in Germany in the framework of the International Barcode of Life (iBOL) Project.

Materials and methods

Fieldwork

A network of taxonomists and citizen scientists collected specimens from Bavaria and from other German states to obtain species which are rare in Bavaria. Field work permits were issued by the responsible state environmental offices of Bavaria [Bayerisches Staatsministerium für Umwelt und Gesundheit, Munich, Germany, project: ‘Barcoding Fauna Bavarica’]. The study sites included more than 537 localities in state forests, public lands and protected areas such as the National Parks ‘Bayerischer Wald’ and ‘Berchtesgadener Land’. The general distribution of all included species, based on literature cited below, can be studied in Fig. S3 and Table S3 (Supporting information).

Specimens and taxonomy

Vouchers from Germany (13 470), Austria (689), Belgium (515), Northern Italy (436), France (392) and other countries (448) are now stored in SNSB-ZSM with the exception of a few specimens in private collections. In 5 years, 538 800 specimens of beetles were collected using various methods (i.e. hand collecting, sweep-netting, Malaise-, window- and pitfall-traps) which were deployed in varied aquatic and terrestrial habitats (Koch 1989, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995a,b, 1996; Köhler, F unpublished, see Figs S1 and S2, Tables S1 and S2, Supporting information). From this total, 462 550 specimens were sorted and identified to a species level and more than 25 000 specimens were submitted for sequence analysis, according to an internal catalogue of missing species (Köhler, F unpublished). Only a few specimens were pinned, and few were more than 5 years old. The number of specimens analysed per species ranged from 1–26 in Adalia bipunctata (Linnaeus, 1758) (see Appendices S1 and S2, Supporting information), available on Dryad doi:10.5061/dryad.gg8fg. Individuals were identified to species level either by Frank Köhler and/or by other taxonomic specialists, using appropriate literature (e.g. Freude et al. 1964-1983; Lohse & Lucht 1989, 1992; Drost et al. 1992; Pfeffer 1994; Hebauer & Klausnitzer 1998; Lompe 2014: http://www.coleo-net.de/coleo/index.htm).

Laboratory protocols

A tissue sample was removed from each specimen and transferred into 96-well plates at the SNSB-ZSM for subsequent DNA extraction. For specimens with a body length >2 mm, a single leg or a leg segment was removed for DNA extraction. The whole voucher was used for some very small specimens (e.g. ≤1 mm, Ptiliidae), but replacement vouchers from the same locality were retained. In other cases (vouchers from Malaise traps), DNA was extracted from the whole voucher at the CCDB (Guelph, Canada) using voucher-recovery protocols and the specimens were repatriated to the SNSB-ZSM for identification and curation. Voucher information such as locality data, habitat, altitude, collector, identifier, taxonomic classifications, habitus images, DNA barcode sequences, primer pairs and trace files are publicly accessible in the ‘German Beetles’ data set in BOLD (http://www.boldsystems.org – data set DOI: dx.doi.org/10.5883/DS-COLBYGER).

Once tissue samples were added, the plates were sent to the Canadian Centre for DNA Barcoding (CCDB) where they were processed using standard barcoding protocols. All protocols for DNA extraction, PCR amplifications and Sanger sequencing procedures are available online under: http://www.dnabarcoding.ca/pa/ge/research/protocols.

All samples were PCR amplified with modified Folmer primers CLepFolF (5′ – ATT CAA CCA ATC ATA AAG ATA TTG G) and CLepFolR (5′ – TAA ACT TCT GGA TGT CCA AAA AAT CA) for the barcoding fragment (5′ CO1), and the same primers were employed for subsequent Sanger sequencing reactions (see also Ivanova et al. 2007; Ward et al. 2008). The sequence data and trace files were uploaded to BOLD and subsequently also to GenBank (accession nos KM439102–KM452702).

Data analysis

Sequence divergences for the barcode region (mean and maximum intraspecific variation and minimum genetic distance to the nearest neighbour species) were calculated using the ‘Barcode Gap Analysis’ tool on BOLD, employing the Kimura-2-Parameter (K2P) distance metric (Puillandre et al. 2012). MUSCLE was applied for sequence alignment restricting analysis to sequences with a minimum length of 500 bp. Neighbour-joining (NJ) trees for each family were calculated following alignment based on K2P distances. The ‘BIN Discordance’ analysis on BOLD was used to reveal species clusters which shared a BIN, and those which were assigned to two or more BINs. BOLD groups sequences into clusters of closely similar CO1 barcode sequences which are assigned a globally unique identifier, termed a ‘Barcode Index Number’ or BIN (Ratnasingham & Hebert 2013). This system can be used to verify the species identifications when taxonomic information is lacking. The BIN System involves a 3-step online pipeline, which clusters similar barcode sequences algorithmically into operational taxonomic units (OTUs). Members of a BIN often belong to a single species as delineated by traditional taxonomy (Hausmann et al. 2013). Every ‘disagreement/conflict’ case is the starting point for re-evaluation of both molecular and morphological data. We follow the concept of integrative taxonomy (Padial et al. 2010; Schlick-Steiner et al. 2010, 2014; Fujita et al. 2012; Riedel et al. 2013) to infer whether there are previously overlooked species in the sample, or if barcode divergence between species is too low or absent to allow the species to be delineated using only CO1.

Results

Barcode sequences (≥500 bp) were obtained from 63% of the 25 294 specimens representing 15 948 specimens from a priori identified species with representatives from 97 of 103 families (94%, Table 1) known from Germany. Success rates were higher for shorter sequences with 71% of specimens generating a ≥300 bp barcode (Fig. 3). Most of the remaining samples (29%) failed to generate a sequence, but a few sequences were flagged by BOLD as contaminations or possible pseudogenes as they contained stop codons. Barcode recovery was very high across a variety of families when proper amounts of tissue were loaded and when specimens were well preserved. The success in barcode recovery ranged from 25% (Eucnemidae) to 91% (Oedemeridae) in families represented by more than 100 species (Table 1). Chi-square analysis (Table S5, Supporting information) revealed that the differences in the success of sequence recovery among families were highly significant (P < 0.00001), suggesting possible problems in primer binding. However, no relationship between specimen size and sequencing success was observed. Only medium-sized (body length 10–14 mm) species with sequences bp were slightly overrepresented (Fig. S4, Table S4, Supporting information). The impacts of variation in specimen age and preservation method (e.g. ethanol concentration) were not evaluated. Based on our experience, average barcode recovery was lower (70%) when specimens were collected in traps, whereas freshly collected material in 95% ethanol provided high success rates (>85%).

Subsequent analyses were restricted to sequence records ≥500 bp (Fig. 1A and B). These 15 948 sequences provided coverage for 3514 German species (53%) that were assigned to 3687 BINs (Fig. 2). In total, 524 new BINs were added to BOLD, most representing new species entries for the BOLD system. Inspection of the sequence clusters in the neighbour-joining (NJ) tree revealed high congruence with morphology-based identifications. In fact, 92.2% of the species could be unambiguously identified by their CO1 sequence. However, in a total of 176 cases, 1089 specimens (6.8%) were represented by more than one BIN, producing a total of 395 BINs for these taxa. Another 42 species pairs and one species trio shared BINS meaning that 409 specimens (2.6%) were involved in BIN sharing. Many of these species pairs (28) could be separated by CO1 because their members were assigned to different subclusters, but 155 specimens (0.97%) including 15 pairs and one trio possessed identical or overlapping CO1 barcode sequences that prevented their discrimination.

Appendix S3 (Supporting information) provides neighbour-joining trees for all families with more than one species. Besides the species name, a voucher number, region and country of origin are given for each specimen (available under doi: 10.5061/dryad.gg8fg).

BIN sharing and paraphyletic species

Our analyses revealed 33 morphologically distinct species clusters (155 specimens) involving 15 pairs and one triplet that either have very low divergence or that share a haplotype (Table 2). As a consequence, the NJ tree failed to recover these taxa as separate monophyletic lineages. We consider two examples here.

Anastrangalia dubia (Scopoli, 1763) and A. reyi (Heyden, 1889) are longhorn beetles (Cerambycidae) that occur throughout Europe with the latter taxon also found in Turkey, Iran, Central Asia, China and Mongolia. The two sexes as well as local populations of the species may have different colours (black, brown and red). The two species are morphologically very similar, but can be separated by the form of the head which has angular margins beneath the eyes in A. dubia, but round ones in A. reyi (Bense 1995). Sequences do not recover either species as a monophyletic cluster (Fig. 4A).

Mycetophagus piceus (Fabricius, 1777) and M. salicis Brisout de Barneville, 1862 are widespread European hairy fungus beetles (Mycetophagidae) which can be separated by the colour of the dorsal surface of their pronotum and elytra and the form of the male genitalia, median lobe and parameres (Lompe 2014). The species are found in different habitats as M. salicis lives in bracket fungus on softwood trees such as willow while M. piceus feeds on bracket fungus overgrown by mycelium on hardwood trees such as oak. Sequences within the BIN do not recover either species as a monophyletic clade, highlighting the need for an in-depth analysis of the status of these two species (Fig. 4B).

BIN sharing with monophyletic species

Another 56 species clusters (254 specimens in 28 pairs) share a BIN, but all of these could be discriminated by barcodes as they showed minimum K2P distances ranging from 0.16% to 2.03% between the specimens belonging to the two different species in each BIN. Moreover, nearly all of these 254 specimens formed monophyletic clusters in the neighbour-joining (NJ) tree and within the BINs (Fig. 5A–D). In the following paragraph, we discuss four cases of well-known species showing low barcode divergences in three families. Table 2 summarizes all cases of BIN sharing found in this study.

The peach weevil Rhynchites bacchus (Linnaeus, 1758) and the cherry weevil R. auratus (Scopoli, 1763) (Attelabidae) are serious pests in fruit orchards (Hassler & Rheinheimer 2010). R. bacchus has a black snout while R. auratus has a metallic snout. The punctation on the pronotum of R. bacchus is coarser than in R. auratus, while the eyes in R. bacchus are strongly prominent, butmore inserted in R. auratus. Although they are morphologically and ecologically distinct species, they share a BIN but show a minimum K2P distance of 1.86% (Fig. 5A).

Agonum scitulum Dejean, 1828 and A. micans (Nicolai, 1822) are two morphologically very similar ground beetles (Carabidae) which can be only separated by the form of male genitalia (Schmidt 2006). A. micans is a Eurosiberian boreotemperate species, strongly associated with wet alder forests on water-logged river and lakeshore soils. It occurs across Europe except in the south, and east into western Siberia. A. scitulum is hygrophilic ground beetle, favoring wet woodlands and well-vegetated marshes, particularly adjacent to tidal rivers. It occurs throughout Europe from western France and Great Britain, to Russia and Romania in the east, southwards to Switzerland. The three specimens of A. scitulum examined in this study shared a distinctive haplotype, but the 14 individuals of A. micans form a paraphyletic assemblage (Fig. 5B).

Harpalus anxius (Duftschmidt, 1812) and H. subcylindricus Dejean, 1829 are ground beetles (Carabidae) which share a BIN but each species forms a distinct cluster (Fig. 5C). H. subcylindricus is restricted to dry, warm, sparsely vegetated habitats such as arid and semi-arid grasslands although it occasionally co-occurs with H. anxius. However, H. anxius is only found on sandy soils, while H. subcylindricus occurs elsewhere. Males can be distinguished by the differing shape of their median lobes, but females cannot be discriminated morphologically (Butterweck et al. 2000).

The sibling species Galerucella aquatica (Geoffroy in Fourcroy, 1785) and G. nymphaeae (Linnaeus, 1758) (Chrysomelidae) employ differing host plants. G. nymphaeae feeds on Nuphar and Nymphaea (water lilies) while G. aquatica consumes Polygonaceae (Lopatin & Nesterova 2005). While males can be identified by the different structure of their genitalia, females cannot be discriminated without knowledge of the host plant (Fig. 5D). However, they can now be recognized using DNA barcoding (minimum K2P distance = 1.23%).

High genetic divergences within species and cases of cryptic diversity

One thousand and eighty-nine specimens in 176 species clusters were assigned to two or more BINs because of their relatively high intraspecific genetic divergences with maximum pairwise K2P distance ranging from a low of 1.60% [Harpalus dimidiatus (Rossi, 1790) represented by two BINs] to 15.75% [Athous vittatus Fabricius, 1793 represented by three BINs]). In total, the 1089 specimens were assigned to 395 BINs (851 specimens in 146 species clusters with two BINs, 121 specimens in 17 species clusters with three BINs, 81 specimens in nine species clusters with four BINs, 26 specimens in two species clusters with five BINs and 10 specimens in one species cluster with six BINs) (Table 3). The balance of this section considers 12 of these cases from various families, breaking them into two categories.

Species with high intraspecific variation without correlated differences in morphology

Four species of Haliplidae (Haliplus furcatus Seidlitz, 1887, H. immaculatus Gerhardt, 1877, H. ruficollis (De Geer, 1774) and H. variegatus Sturm, 1834) show high intraspecific divergences from 1.23% in H. variegatus to 2.66% in H. immaculatus (Table 3) (Fig. 6A). However, in contrast to H. lineatocollis (Marsham, 1802) (see below), morphological analysis of the voucher specimens (performed by the first author) did not reveal evidence of morphological divergence between the specimens in each cluster.

The false ladybird Endomychus coccineus (Linnaeus, 1758) (Endomychidae) belongs to a monotypic genus that is widespread in Central European forests. The larvae are often prevalent on fungi growing on birch and beech stumps. The maximum intraspecific divergence (ISD) between the two BINs is 3.12% (Table 3) (Fig. 6B).

Trichodes apiarius Herbst, 1792 a checkered beetle, is the most common species of the genus in Central Europe. Its larval stage parasitizes bees, predating on the larvae and nymphs of both solitary bees (e.g. Osmia and Megachile) and honey bees. The adults feed on the pollen of flowers, mainly Apiaceae, in May through June (Niehuis 2013). The maximum intraspecific divergence (ISD) between the two BINs is 3.44% (Table 3) (Fig. 6C).

Possible cases of cryptic diversity

The following paragraph provides details for nine possible cases of cryptic diversity involving species clusters, most with more than 5% divergence. For Corymbia rubra (Linnaeus, 1758) and Leptinus testaceus Müller, 1817 minimum pairwise distances are 3.45% and 2.49%, respectively (Table 3), but no closely related sister species are known from Central Europe.

Athous vittatus Fabricius, 1793 is a common click beetle (Elateridae) with variable dorsal coloration (Laibner 2000). Several colour forms have been described and named. The fact that specimens of this species were divided into three clusters with a maximum divergence of 15.75% suggests that this taxon is actually composed of two if not three species in Germany (Fig. 6D).

Procraerus tibialis (Lacordaire, 1835), another elaterid, belongs to a monotypic genus in Europe and occurs in the cavities of deciduous trees infested by Rhamnusium bicolor (Schrank, 1781) (Cerambycidae) and cossonine weevils (Husler & Husler 1940). The adults are only active at night, remaining hidden in crevices or under bark during the day. Adults can be reared from dry wood of old oaks (Németh & Merkl 2009). A single specimen from southern Bavaria possessed a Max ISD of 13.64% from a cluster of nine specimens (Table 3) collected in different regions of Germany including northern Bavaria (Fig. 6E). As one junior synonym (Ampedus subcarintus Germar, 1844) exists for this species, further specimens from Europe should be barcoded including the type specimens of both taxa to clarify the taxonomic status of the barcode lineages.

Hydrobius fuscipes (Linnaeus, 1758) is one of the most widespread water scavenger beetles (Hydrophilidae) in lentic habitats across the entire Holarctic region including North America, China and Mongolia (Hansen 1987). Three morphological variants of this species from Germany were named in the past, but were later synonymized and have not been ranked as species or subspecies in recent faunal treatments (Drost et al. 1992; Hebauer & Klausnitzer 1998). Taking into account the geographical scale and number of specimens studied (n = 15), the barcode results suggest that at least four (probably) allopatric species occur in Germany (Table 3), with an additional taxon in Greece (Fig. 6F). The occurrence of these lineages needs to be investigated across the whole distribution of this probable species complex. Morphometric data and additional molecular markers were recently assembled for a comprehensive study examining the boundaries of this species complex in Fennoscandia. Their study includes examination of available type material and support the presence of four species in addition to the barcode clusters found in our study, including H. arcticus and the formally established morphological variants of H. fuscipes (Fossen 2014; E. I. Fossen, T. Ekrem, J. Bergsten & A. Nilsson, unpublished).

Corymbia rubra (Linnaeus, 1758), the red-brown longhorn beetle (Cerambycidae), is a well-known xylophagous inhabitant of coniferous forests throughout Central Europe whose larvae feed in the dead wood of spruce and pine trees. The distinctive colour of this species has traditionally allowed a straightforward identification (Bense 1995). As a result, it is remarkable that this taxon likely includes two species as evidenced by the presence of 3.45% divergence (Table 3) between members of the two clusters (Fig. 6G). However, there remains a need for more comprehensive, integrative investigations to validate this conclusion.

The well-known thistle tortoise beetle (Chrysomelidae) Cassida rubiginosa Müller, 1776 feeds on Canada thistle (Cirsium arvense) and was intentionally introduced to the United States and New Zealand to control thistles (Asadi et al. 2013). Given its importance as a biological control agent, it is interesting that it is represented by at least three distinct clades in Germany (Fig. 7A).

Lixus iridis (Olivier, 1807), one of the largest (body length = 17 mm) weevils (Curculionidae) in Germany (Hassler & Rheinheimer 2010), is represented by two barcode clades. All voucher specimens have been carefully checked by specialists to exclude misidentification. The Bavarian specimen differs by 7.15% (Table 3) from a clade with seven specimens from Rhineland Palatinate (Germany) (Fig. 7B). Interestingly, the exceptional specimen shows sequence congruence with unpublished records for this species from Finland.

Ocypus ophthalmicus (Scopoli, 1763) is an easily identified rove beetle (Staphylinidae) because of its shiny blue coloration and large size with recent records from all states in Germany (Köhler & Klausnitzer 1998) from deciduous forests and xeric habitats, including urban areas (Kleeberg & Uhlig 2011). From most parts of Germany, only the nominotypical taxon is recorded, but nine synonyms have been designated from other regions of Europe, and six subspecies are recognized (Drugmand 1998). Although our data only include six records (Table 3), they suggest that more than one species occurs in Germany (Fig. 7C). Additional material from all parts of the country is needed to clarify the status of this species.

Haliplus lineatocollis (Marsham, 1802) is a common, mainly lotic and, compared to most other members of the family Haliplidae, easy to identify species which occurs in alkaline, slow-flowing streams, ditches and gravel pits. The larvae, and perhaps also the adults, feed on filamentous algae (van Vondel 1997). According to the leading taxonomic specialist for this group (Bernhard van Vondel, pers. comm.) subtle morphological differences support the presence of three species in Europe with two occurring in Germany (Fig. 7D). It will be a complex task to resolve their taxonomic status because more than 14 junior synonyms (see Nilsson & van Vondel 2005) will need to be studied, and it is desirable to extend the genetic analyses as well.

Leptinus testaceus is a small, pale, eyeless beetle of the family Leiodidae that lives in the nests of small mammals throughout Central Europe (Kreissl 1988). In the western Palearctic region, six species of the genus have been described (Besuchet 1980). The current barcode results suggest (Table 3) that the Central European Leptinus fauna is more diverse than expected although more samples need to be examined to confirm this hypothesis (Fig. 7E).

Discussion

This study establishes that DNA barcoding is an effective tool for fast, reliable species identification of Central European beetles. Other studies, focusing, for example on Bavarian, German or European species of Lepidoptera (Hausmann et al. 2011a,b, 2013), Hymenoptera (S. Schmidt, C. Schmidd-Egger, J. Morinière, A. Hausmann, G. Haszprunar & P. D. N. Hebert, in prep.), Neuropterida (Morinière et al. 2014), Heteroptera (Raupach et al. 2014), Myriapoda (Spelda et al. 2011) and Orthoptera (O. Hawlitschek, J. Morinière, S. Schmidt, F. Glaw, A. Hausmann & G. Haszprunar, in prep.) have obtained similar results, strongly suggesting the efficacy of DNA barcoding for all arthropods. Approximately 42% of the Central European fauna of beetles and 53% of the species known from Germany are now represented in the publicly available reference library on BOLD. Despite the fact that taxonomic research on German Coleoptera has been underway for more than 200 years, our study revealed 209 cases where the results from DNA barcoding and traditional taxonomy are discordant. These conflicts involved 176 cases of deep intraspecific divergence (1089 specimens) and 31 species clusters (155 specimens) which shared their barcodes, taxa which should be especially targeted for further sampling in future barcoding projects in Europe. These results indicate both to the presence of very recent species and potentially overlooked species diversity, cases are summarized in Tables 1 and 2. Such incompatibilities between barcodes and traditional taxonomy are not surprising as evolution is an ongoing process and lineage idiosyncratic performance of DNA barcoding or the molecular biodiversity assessment approach have been well documented (Hendrich et al. 2010). The relatively high number of 1089 specimens, representing 176 potentially overlooked species was surprising, especially because many of these cases did not involve the specious and taxonomically difficult Staphylinidae, Curculionidae and Elateridae but the well-studied Carabidae, Cerambycidae, Haliplidae and Hydrophilidae.

We encourage the coleopteran scientific community to join the DNA barcoding projects on BOLD, to aid clarification of the status of species and to assist in the description of possibly overlooked species. Discussion and commenting on specific specimens on BOLD is possible for all registered users. As the presence of nuclear mitochondrial DNA (NUMTs) is a known problem in DNA barcoding (Jordal & Kambestad 2014), we double checked the trace files for the presence of double peaks and stop codons (the latter regularly carried out by the CCDB, Guelph, in the sequence editing process). We could not find any evidence of either complexity in the observed cases. All suspicious cases of BIN sharing and cryptic diversity candidates were, moreover, compared with DNA barcode reference libraries constructed by colleagues involved in other European DNA barcoding initiatives (FINBOL, Mikko Pentinsaari; PASSIFOR, Rodolphe Rougerie). Future investigations focusing on possibly overlooked species should couple the barcode analysis of more specimens from all parts of Europe with expert morphological reappraisals and the examination of variation in nuclear genes (see Bergsten et al. 2012a,b) or extensive screening of the genome for nucleotide polymorphisms (i.e. SNPs).
